&lt;img src=&quot;/%3Ca%20mce_thref=&quot; title=&quot;Stan and Ollie and a Drive Through Bunker Hill by SilentEchoes57, on Flickr&quot; /&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://farm7.static.flickr.com/6202/6128834165_9dbec163a0.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Stan and Ollie and a Drive Through Bunker Hill&quot; height=&quot;163&quot; width=&quot;500&quot; /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
The footage not only provides a wonderful glimpse of post-WWII Bunker 
Hill, now lost to civic redevelopment, but illuminates Los Angeles 
during the silent film era as well.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
As I explain in my book &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.amazon.com/Silent-Visions-Discovering-Hollywood-Through/dp/1595800573/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&#038;ie=UTF8&#038;qid=1315549782&#038;sr=1-2&quot;&gt;Silent Visions&lt;/a&gt;, Harold Lloyd filmed scenes for 
seven different movies at the intersection of 3rd and Grand, on Bunker 
Hill, more scenes than at any other location in Los Angeles. It was a 
popular place for Laurel and Hardy, and other Hal Roach Studio stars to 
film as well. The Prelinger film drives twice by Lloydâ€<img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/13.0.1/72x72/2122.png" alt="™" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" />s intersection of
3rd and Grand, providing razor sharp images of where Lloyd and other 
silent stars filmed.
&lt;/p&gt;
